The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Usha Martin net leaps 

 A STAFF REPORTER

 Usha Martin managing director Rajeev Jhawar (centre) and joint MD P. Bhattacharya (left) in Calcutta on Wednesday. Picture by Kishor Roy Chowdhury

 Calcutta, May 11: Usha Martin Limited has registered a 163 per cent growth in net profit at Rs 40.87 crore in 2004-05 against Rs 15.52 crore in the previous fiscal.

 The gross revenue of the company increased 46 per cent at Rs 1,270.58 crore compared with Rs 868.77 crore a year ago. Profit before tax rose 150 per cent to Rs 58.28 crore from Rs 23.27 crore in the previous fiscal.

 The companys exports business reported a robust performance. Exports were up 104 per cent at Rs 432 crore during the period under review compared with Rs 212 crore a year earlier. 

 The board has recommended a dividend of 30 per cent for 2004-05.

 For the current fiscal, the company is targeting a gross turnover of Rs 1,450 crore and a group turnover of Rs 2,600 crore. The net turnover of the group is expected to be Rs 1,850 crore.

 The consolidated net profit of Usha Martin Ltd grew 228 per cent at Rs 50.38 per cent last fiscal against Rs 15.34 per cent in the previous year. The consolidated gross revenue posted a 44 per cent growth at Rs 1,648.48 crore, up from Rs 1,145.39 crore reported in the previous year. 

 The company had signed a memorandum of understanding with JCT Ltd to acquire the latters steel-wire and wire-rope division at Hoshiarpur in Punjab.

 Usha Martin joint managing director P. Bhattacharya said, We shall take management control of the company within the next two weeks. We expect a potential gross turnover addition of Rs 150 crore, the net benefit being around Rs 75 crore, from the acquisition. 

 The JCT unit has a production capacity of 3,000 tonnes per month, of which it is currently utilising around 70 per cent.

 The company is also eyeing acquisitions in the US for its steel-wire rope business. It already has manufacturing facilities in the UK, Thailand and the UAE.

 We shall utilise the acquisition in the US to manufacture train, elevator, mining and construction ropes. The ideal plant capacity should be at least 500 tonnes per month, which shall be scaled up depending on the requirements, said Rajeev Jhawar, managing director, Usha Martin.

 The company has also adopted for backward integration by entering into iron-ore and coal mining. We have been allotted iron-ore and coal mines at Jharkhand. The capacity of the coal mine is estimated at 25 million tonnes, Jhawar said.




